description.plain: “Whiskey Lullaby” is the title of a country song composed by Bill Anderson and Jon Randall. It was first recorded by Brad Paisley as a duet with Alison Krauss on Paisley’s 2003 album Mud on the Tires, and released on April 12, 2004, as that album’s third single, and the eleventh chart single of Paisley’s career. The song reached a peak of number three on the Billboard Hot Country Singles & Tracks (now Hot Country Songs) charts, and 41 on the Billboard Hot 100. The song won the 2005 Country Music Association Song of the Year award. It is one of Paisley’s three songs certified Platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America, the others being “She’s Everything” and “Then”.

description.plain:
Cowritten by Brad Paisley, Kelley Lovelace, and Lee Thomas Miller, “I’m Still A Guy” was released in March 2008 as the fourth single from Paisley’s album, 5th Gear (an auto reference)

The song is mid-tempo and set in triple meter. The lyrical contrast of masculine and feminine archetypes is intended, according to Paisley, to “capture this struggle a little bit between men and women in a playful way.”

More specifically, the song is a discussion of gender stereotypes.  Since it is essentially a celebration of hetero-normative notions of masculinity, it is very similar to some contemporary rap songs, like 50 Cent’s “In Da Club,” a so-called “brag track” detailing the performer’s “masculine” identity.

In Paisley’s case, the first-person narration articulates the differences between the singer and his romantic partner, who we can assume is a female because all of the indicators in the song seem to allow for exclusively heterosexual relationships.  The “you” of this song, therefore, is the narrator’s girlfriend or wife, for whom, by association with the narrator’s cliche masculinity, femininity is also caricatured.

One thing comes across clearly in Brad’s light-hearted play on these stereotypes: gender is always a performance.

A country song with similar stereotypical masculine themes was released by Tracy Byrd in 2003. He was joined by Blake Shelton, Andy Griggs and and Montgomery Gentry on * The Truth About Men *

description.plain:

“We Danced” is the fourth and final single from Brad Paisley’s debut album, Who Needs Pictures. Lyrically, it talks about the beginning of a romance, and how the relationship came full circle––they danced when they met and danced before their engagement.

Commercially, it was successful, becoming his fourth straight entry on both the Billboard Hot 100 and Hot Country Songs. On the former, it became his (at the time) highest charting single, reaching 29, and topped the latter, becoming his second number one.

description.plain:
This playful track about two friends deciding to start a band is a duet with Keith Urban. Paisley and the New Zealand singer have been friends since before either of them had record deals.

This is one of four vocal tracks from Paisley’s mainly instrumental album “Play”. When this reached #1 on the Hot Country Songs chart, it became the 13th chart-topper for Paisley and the ninth for Urban.

Paisley and Urban were the first male duo to have a country #1 since Kenny Chesney and Uncle Kracker reigned for five weeks in April and May 2004 with “When the Sun Goes Down.”

“Start A Band” was nominated for a Grammy Award for the title Best Country Collaboration With Vocals at the 52nd Grammy Awards, but lost to “I Told You So” by Carrie Underwood.

Brad Paisley writes in the liner notes of “Play”:

“People have been asking for years when Keith and I would do something like this. I am so honored to get to finally pick and sing with one of my favorite players in the world. I am so humbled by his talent.”

description.plain: “Keep On the Sunny Side” was written by Ada Blenkhorn and Howard Entwisle in 1899, and became famous in the late 1920s when it was recorded by the Carter Family.  The version here by Paisley is a faithful acoustic cover of the song with a good clear digital recording. The fiddle, mandolin and guitar parts are very good, and Paisley gives a sincere and positive vocal.
